      title: "Continuous Measurement: Dimensions and Selection Logic",
      body: "Behavioral measurement is the foundation on which all claims about behavior change rest. Johnston and Pennypacker (1993) argued that behavior is inherently dimensional — it occupies time, it has frequency, it produces effects — and that the dimension selected for measurement must correspond to the dimension that is clinically relevant. Selecting the wrong dimension produces data that is collected reliably and answers the wrong question entirely.\n\nContinuous measurement captures every instance of a target behavior in real time. It is the methodological standard against which all other measurement approaches are evaluated, and the default assumption of BCBA exam scenarios unless a specific clinical constraint justifies a less precise alternative.\n\nFrequency and Rate: Frequency is a raw count of behavioral instances. Its limitation is context-dependence — 12 responses in a 10-minute session is not the same as 12 responses in a 60-minute session. Rate resolves this by expressing frequency as responses per unit time. Cooper, Heron, and Heward (2020) are explicit that rate is the preferred metric whenever session durations vary across observers or settings.\n\nDuration: Duration quantifies total elapsed time during which a behavior is occurring. It is the appropriate dimension when clinical severity is a function of how long a behavior persists, not how many times it starts. Three instances of self-injury lasting 30 minutes each is categorically different from 20 instances lasting 45 seconds each — frequency renders these indistinguishable.\n\nLatency: Latency is the elapsed time between the onset of an antecedent stimulus and the onset of the response. The exam frequently conflates latency with duration — the distinction is that latency measures the interval before the response begins, duration measures the interval the response occupies.\n\nInterresponse Time (IRT): IRT measures elapsed time between the end of one response and the beginning of the next. It captures distributional information about response spacing that aggregate rate data obscures, and is most appropriate when the temporal patterning of behavior is the clinical target."
