      body: "The reversal design is the most direct single-case method for demonstrating experimental control. By withdrawing the independent variable and returning to baseline conditions, the analyst tests whether behavior reverts — and by reintroducing the IV, tests whether the effect replicates. Three conditions must be met to claim a functional relationship: behavior changes in the expected direction when the IV is introduced, reverts toward baseline when withdrawn, and changes again upon reintroduction. Each phase change is a within-subject replication of the effect.\n\nThe design's strength is also its primary limitation. Withdrawal requires that behavior be reversible — that removing the IV will actually produce a return toward baseline. For behaviors that are maintained by the natural environment once acquired, or where reversal poses clinical harm, the design is inappropriate. A client who learns to request items using a communication device during intervention will likely continue requesting after the device protocol is withdrawn — the behavior has contacted natural reinforcement and is no longer under experimental control of the IV alone.\n\nAdditionally, ethical constraints sometimes prohibit withdrawal — particularly when the target behavior is dangerous or when returning to baseline conditions exposes the client to harm. In these cases, multiple baseline or changing criterion designs provide experimental control without requiring withdrawal.\n\nThe exam will present scenarios and ask whether reversal is appropriate. The answer turns on two questions: Is the behavior change reversible? Is withdrawal ethical?"
