      title: "Multiple Baseline Design: Replication Without Withdrawal",
      body: "The multiple baseline design demonstrates experimental control by staggering the introduction of the IV across two or more tiers — different behaviors, subjects, or settings — while continuously measuring all tiers. The logic is replication without withdrawal: if behavior in each tier changes only when the IV is introduced to that tier, and not before, a functional relationship is supported.\n\nThree variants: across behaviors (same person, different target behaviors), across subjects (same behavior, different people), and across settings (same behavior and person, different environments). The across-subjects variant provides the strongest external validity argument because it demonstrates the effect generalizes across individuals.\n\nThe primary internal validity threat is concurrent change — if behavior improves across all tiers simultaneously before the IV reaches them, something other than the IV is responsible. This is called a 'multiple baseline failure' and is detected by monitoring untreated tiers continuously during the study.\n\nA critical design requirement is tier independence — the behaviors, subjects, or settings across tiers must be functionally independent. If improving behavior in one tier automatically improves behavior in another (because they share a common controlling variable), the staggered introduction of the IV cannot demonstrate control — it merely reveals an existing dependency.\n\nThe multiple-probe variant, developed by Horner and Baer (1978), uses intermittent rather than continuous baseline probes — reducing reactivity and measurement burden while preserving experimental logic."
