      body: "Functional behavior assessment encompasses a continuum of methods ranging from indirect (informant-based) to direct (observational) to experimental (functional analysis). Indirect assessment — including structured interviews, rating scales, and record review — is always the starting point of an FBA, but it is never the endpoint.\n\nStructured interviews such as the Functional Assessment Interview (FAI; O'Neill et al., 1997) and the Behavior Analyst Skill Builder guides systematically gather information about antecedents, consequences, setting events, behavioral history, and the contexts in which behavior is most and least likely to occur. Rating scales such as the Motivation Assessment Scale (MAS; Durand & Crimmins, 1988) and the Questions About Behavioral Function (QABF; Matson & Vollmer, 1995) ask informants to rate behavior across functional categories and produce a profile of hypothesized maintaining variables.\n\nThe critical limitation of indirect assessment is informant dependence. Informants are subject to recall bias, observational limitations, and interpretive frameworks that may not map onto behavioral contingencies accurately. Research comparing indirect assessment outcomes to functional analysis outcomes has consistently found poor correspondence — informants frequently identify the wrong function, particularly when behavior is automatically maintained or when multiple functions are operating simultaneously.\n\nThe BACB Ethics Code (2020) requires that assessment be appropriate to the presenting problem. Using indirect assessment alone to design a restrictive intervention — without direct observation or functional analysis — fails to meet this standard and constitutes an ethical, not just methodological, problem."
